---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="center" style="--scale-from: 3.5;--fragment-duration: 1s">
  <h3
    p-effect="zoom fade"
    style="font-size: 0.6em; opacity: 0.6; margin-block-end: 0.5em;"
  >
    your MCP server is on the internet now...
  </h3>
  <h2 p-effect="zoom fade" style="font-size: 1.5em;">
    <span class="main-gradient">who's allowed to call it?</span> 🤔
  </h2>
  <p
    p-effect="zoom fade"
    style="font-size: 0.6em; margin-block-start: 1em; opacity: 0.7;"
  >
    MCP answers this with <strong>OAuth 2.1 + PKCE</strong>
  </p>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      stdio is inherently more controlled: the host starts a local process and
      communicates with it directly. But a remote HTTP MCP server is exposed
      over the network, so we need a standard way to authorize clients and
      users.
    </p>
    <p>
      MCP does not invent a custom auth mechanism here. It builds on OAuth 2.1,
      PKCE, and standard OAuth metadata discovery.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 style="margin-block-end: 0.2rem;" class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
    HTTP Authentication
  </h2>
  <h3 style="margin-block-start: 0.8rem;">OAuth 2.1 + PKCE 🔐</h3>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      For remote MCP servers, authorization is handled at the HTTP transport
      layer. The MCP server behaves like a protected resource server. The OAuth
      authorization server can be the same application, or an external identity
      provider.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
    What is PKCE - Proof Key for Code Exchange?
  </h3>
  <ul>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🧪 Client creates a random <code>code_verifier</code>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧬 Sends only a hashed <code>code_challenge</code> during login
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🎫 Sends the original <code>code_verifier</code> when exchanging the code
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🛡️ Prevents stolen authorization codes from being reused
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      PKCE is an extension to the OAuth Authorization Code flow. The client
      starts by generating a random secret called code_verifier. Instead of
      sending the secret directly, it sends a hashed version called
      code_challenge.
    </p>
    <p>
      Later, when the client exchanges the authorization code for an access
      token, it must send the original code_verifier. The authorization server
      hashes it again and checks that it matches the original challenge.
    </p>
    <p>
      This means that stealing the authorization code is not enough to obtain an
      access token. Without the original verifier, the token exchange fails.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">The OAuth flow in MCP</h3>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9em">
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🚪 <span class="main-sub-gradient">1. Unauthorized request</span> — client calls
      the MCP endpoint without a token
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🔍 <span class="main-sub-gradient">2. Resource discovery</span> — server points
      to its protected resource metadata
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🧭 <span class="main-sub-gradient">3. Auth server discovery</span> — client
      finds authorization and token endpoints
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      👤 <span class="main-sub-gradient">4. Authorization</span> — user logs in and
      grants permission
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🎫 <span class="main-sub-gradient">5. Token exchange</span> — client gets an
      access token using PKCE
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      ✅ <span class="main-sub-gradient">6. Authenticated requests</span> — token
      sent as <code>Authorization: Bearer</code>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The important MCP-specific part is the discovery chain. The client does
      not start by guessing the authorization endpoint. First it discovers the
      protected resource metadata for the MCP server.
    </p>
    <p>
      That metadata tells the client which authorization server should be used.
      Then the client reads the authorization server metadata to find the login
      endpoint, token endpoint, supported PKCE methods, and so on.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 1em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
      1. Protected Resource Metadata
    </span>
    🔍
  </h3>

  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource">
  <code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-json">{
      "resource": "https://my-mcp-server.com/mcp",
      "authorization_servers": [
        "https://auth.my-mcp-server.com"
      ],
      "scopes_supported": [
        "orders:read",
        "orders:write"
      ],
      "bearer_methods_supported": [
        "header"
      ]
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is the MCP-specific discovery step. The MCP server is the protected
      resource. It exposes metadata that tells the client which authorization
      server can issue valid tokens for this resource.
    </p>
    <p>
      The key field here is authorization_servers. It points to the OAuth
      authorization server. This can be the same origin as the MCP server, or a
      separate identity provider.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 1em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
      2. Authorization Server Metadata
    </span>
    🧭
  </h3>

  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="https://auth.my-mcp-server.com/.well-known/oauth-authorization-server">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-json">
  {
    "issuer": "https://auth.my-mcp-server.com",
    "authorization_endpoint": "https://auth.my-mcp-server.com/oauth/authorize",
    "token_endpoint": "https://auth.my-mcp-server.com/oauth/token",
    "registration_endpoint": "https://auth.my-mcp-server.com/oauth/register",
    "response_types_supported": ["code"],
    "code_challenge_methods_supported": ["S256"]
  }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is standard OAuth authorization server metadata. Once the MCP client
      knows which authorization server to use, it fetches this document to learn
      where to redirect the user, where to exchange the authorization code, and
      whether dynamic client registration is supported.
    </p>
    <p>
      S256 is the PKCE method we care about. The client creates a code verifier,
      sends the code challenge during authorization, and later proves possession
      of the verifier during the token exchange.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide follow-fragments>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 0.6em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
      Becoming an OAuth provider
    </span>
    🛡️
  </h3>

  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.js">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">  import { betterAuth } from "better-auth";
  import { jwt } from "better-auth/plugins";
  import { oauthProvider } from "@better-auth/oauth-provider";

  const auth = betterAuth({
    baseURL: AUTH_BASE_URL,
    secret: process.env.BETTER_AUTH_SECRET,
    disabledPaths: ["/token"],
    plugins: [
      </code><p-fragment><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">jwt({ disableSettingJwtHeader: true }),
      oauthProvider({
        loginPage: "/sign-in",
        consentPage: "/consent",
        allowDynamicClientRegistration: true,
        allowUnauthenticatedClientRegistration: true,
      }),
    ],
    socialProviders: {
      github: {
        clientId: process.env.GITHUB_ID,
        clientSecret: process.env.GITHUB_SECRET,
      },
    },
  });</code></p-fragment></pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      In this example, better-auth becomes the authorization server. It handles
      login, consent, token issuance, and dynamic client registration.
    </p>
    <p>
      The MCP server itself is still the protected resource. It does not need to
      implement the whole OAuth flow manually. It only needs to advertise where
      authorization happens and validate the access tokens it receives.
    </p>
    <p>
      allowUnauthenticatedClientRegistration is useful for MCP clients because
      they may need to register dynamically as public clients before starting
      the authorization flow.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide follow-fragments>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 1em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">Protecting the endpoint</span>
    🔒
  </h3>

  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.js">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">  import { verifyAccessToken } from "better-auth/oauth2";
  import { toNodeHandler } from "better-auth/node";

  const app = express();

  app.all("/api/auth/*", toNodeHandler(auth));
  app.use(express.json());

    app.post("/mcp", async (req, res) => {
    const accessToken = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, "");

    </code><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">try {
      </code><code p-fragment p-effect="highlight" style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">await verifyAccessToken(accessToken, {
        verifyOptions: {
          issuer: AUTH_BASE_URL,
          audience: MCP_RESOURCE_URL,
        },
      });</code><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">
    } catch {
      </code><code p-fragment p-effect="highlight" style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">res.set(
        "WWW-Authenticate",
        `Bearer resource_metadata="${MCP_RESOURCE_URL}/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource"`
      );

      return res.status(401).json({ error: "unauthorized" });</code><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">
    }

    const transport = new StreamableHTTPServerTransport({
      sessionIdGenerator: undefined,
    });

    const server = createServer();

    await server.connect(transport);
    await transport.handleRequest(req, res, req.body);
  });</code>
    </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The MCP endpoint is protected like any other resource server endpoint. It
      expects a Bearer access token and validates issuer, audience, expiry, and
      signature.
    </p>
    <p>
      If validation fails, the server returns 401 and includes a
      WWW-Authenticate header. The important part is resource_metadata: it tells
      the MCP client where to find the protected resource metadata document.
    </p>
    <p>
      From there, the client discovers the authorization server, performs the
      OAuth flow with PKCE, obtains an access token, and retries the MCP
      request.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3>
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
      Don't build OAuth from scratch
    </span>
    🙏
  </h3>

  <ul>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      📦 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Pick an auth layer</span>
      <span class="item-sub"
        ><code>@auth/core</code> / <code>better-auth</code></span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      ☁️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">Or use an identity provider</span>
      <span class="item-sub"
        ><code>Clerk</code> / <code>Auth0</code> / <code>Keycloak</code></span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      👀 MCP SDKs are adding <span class="main-sub-gradient">
        auth and OAuth helpers
      </span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Implementing OAuth from scratch is easy to get wrong. Use a library or a
      hosted provider whenever possible.
    </p>
    <p>
      The MCP-specific part is not “invent OAuth again”. It is wiring standard
      OAuth discovery, protected resource metadata, token validation, and the
      MCP transport together.
    </p>
    <p>
      Also, check the exact SDK and version you are using. OAuth helper support
      is evolving quickly, so avoid promising that every SDK version already has
      everything built in.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<style lang="scss">
  ul {
    li[p-fragment]:not(:last-of-type) {
      margin-block-end: 0.75em;
    }
  }

  .item-sub {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.72em;
    font-style: italic;
    color: #484848;
    margin-inline-start: 1.5em;
    margin-block-start: 0.2em;

    code {
      font-style: normal;
      font-size: 0.95em;
    }
  }
</style>
